---
/**
 * /map — the interactive impact-study map.
 *
 * The interactive workspace used to share the homepage hero with
 * the brand block and workflow animation. Now it has its own page
 * where it can fill the viewport without competing for attention.
 * The homepage hero links here via "See the map".
 *
 * Layout: a slim framing header above the workspace (so a visitor
 * landing directly on /map knows what they're looking at), the
 * MapWorkspace itself, then a compact CTA band below that converts
 * the curiosity the map generates into a Sign-up click. Both the
 * header and CTA are intentionally low-density so the map remains
 * the focal point.
 */
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import MapWorkspace from '../components/MapWorkspace.astro';
import NetworkSection from '../components/NetworkSection.astro';
import '../styles/global.css';
import '../styles/nav.css';
import '../styles/footer.css';
import '../styles/map-page.css';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Map | Lumecon"
  description="Run a live economic-impact study on any state, county, or tribal land. Hover any region to inspect; click to run a study with Cedar AI. US coverage today, international scope on the roadmap."
  canonical="https://lumecon.ai/map"
  keywords="Lumecon map, interactive economic impact map, state economic impact, county economic impact, tribal economic impact, AIANNH boundaries, alternative data economic analysis, high-frequency data, IMPLAN alternative, RIMS II alternative, REMI alternative, BEA RIMS"
  ogTitle="Lumecon map: live economic-impact studies on every state, county, and tribal land"
  ogDescription="Hover or click any region to run an economic impact study in minutes rather than months. Economic impact analysis designed for the 21st century, covering all US geographies today with international scope on the roadmap."
>
  <Nav />
  <main class="map-page">

    <!-- Framing header. Tells a direct-link visitor what they're
         looking at + how to use it, without taking enough space to
         push the map below the fold on a typical laptop. -->
    <header class="map-page__header">
      <div class="map-page__header-inner">
        <p class="map-page__kicker">Interactive demo</p>
        <h1 class="map-page__title reveal-soft hl-block hl-block--green-b">Run an economic impact study.</h1>
        <p class="map-page__sub">Hover any region to inspect it, or click to run a study with Cedar across full reservation, state, and national scope in minutes rather than months.</p>
        <p class="map-page__roadmap">US coverage today; international scope is on the roadmap.</p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <MapWorkspace />

    <!-- "What kickstarts a study." Four input tiles naming the
         records Cedar takes: financial records, the things your
         org spends on, the time window, and the place. Lobbying
         and marketing are NOT inputs — those are use cases for the
         study (handled in "Why it matters" below). Icons come
         first, then the explainer text mentioning the public
         datasets Cedar pulls alongside what you supply. -->
    <section class="map-page__inputs" aria-labelledby="map-inputs-title">
      <div class="map-page__about-inner">
        <p class="map-page__about-kicker">What kickstarts a study</p>
        <h2 class="map-page__about-title reveal-soft hl-block hl-block--gold-b" id="map-inputs-title">The inputs you already have.</h2>
        <ul class="map-page__inputs-grid" aria-label="Study inputs">
          <li class="map-page__input">
            <span class="map-page__input-icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"><rect x="3.5" y="5.5" width="17" height="14" rx="1"/><line x1="3.5" y1="9" x2="20.5" y2="9"/><line x1="8" y1="3" x2="8" y2="7"/><line x1="16" y1="3" x2="16" y2="7"/><rect x="6.5" y="11.6" width="2.4" height="2.4" fill="currentColor" stroke="none"/><rect x="10.8" y="11.6" width="2.4" height="2.4" fill="currentColor" stroke="none"/><rect x="15.1" y="11.6" width="2.4" height="2.4" fill="currentColor" stroke="none"/><rect x="6.5" y="15.4" width="2.4" height="2.4" fill="currentColor" stroke="none"/><rect x="10.8" y="15.4" width="2.4" height="2.4" fill="currentColor" stroke="none"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="map-page__input-label">Year &amp; range</span>
          </li>
          <li class="map-page__input">
            <span class="map-page__input-icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"><path d="M12 2.5 C7.6 2.5 4.5 5.8 4.5 9.6 C4.5 15.4 12 21.5 12 21.5 C12 21.5 19.5 15.4 19.5 9.6 C19.5 5.8 16.4 2.5 12 2.5 Z"/><circle cx="12" cy="9.6" r="2.6"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="map-page__input-label">Geography</span>
          </li>
          <li class="map-page__input">
            <span class="map-page__input-icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linejoin="miter"><path d="M5 3.5 H14.5 L19.5 8.5 V20.5 H5 Z"/><line x1="7.5" y1="11.5" x2="17" y2="11.5"/><line x1="7.5" y1="14" x2="17" y2="14"/><line x1="7.5" y1="16.5" x2="13" y2="16.5"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="map-page__input-label">Audited financials &amp; payroll</span>
          </li>
          <li class="map-page__input">
            <span class="map-page__input-icon" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"><path d="M12 20.5 L4.5 13 C2.7 11.3 3 8 5.3 6.8 C7.3 5.7 9.4 6.6 10.5 8.1 L12 9.7 L13.5 8.1 C14.6 6.6 16.7 5.7 18.7 6.8 C21 8 21.3 11.3 19.5 13 Z"/></svg>
            </span>
            <span class="map-page__input-label">Charitable giving &amp; other spending</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <details class="map-page__inputs-more">
          <summary class="map-page__inputs-more-summary">
            <span>How the data comes together</span>
            <span class="map-page__inputs-more-chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="map-page__inputs-more-body">
            <p class="map-page__inputs-lede">Drop in what you already have. We layer it with the public data the study needs (ACS, BEA, LODES, QCEW, CBP, USASpending, the regional Fed banks), the alternative data modern models lean on (higher-frequency feeds, mobility, and other non-traditional signals), and our own proprietary multipliers refined across thousands of past studies plus methodology our team developed in-house. Every study covers county, state, reservation, and national geography at every tier, so wherever your work creates impact, the study finds it.</p>
            <p class="map-page__inputs-lede">The workspace is built so an organization of any size can actually collect the data, not just clean it. Review queues route the pieces to HR, finance, payroll, program, and council reviewers, so the study doesn&rsquo;t stall on a single analyst&rsquo;s desk waiting on a file someone else has.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- "What you're seeing." Collapsible by default. Visitors who
         want the explainer expand it; visitors who already get it
         scan past without a wall of text in their face. -->
    <section class="map-page__about" aria-labelledby="map-about-title">
      <div class="map-page__about-inner">
        <details class="map-page__details">
          <summary class="map-page__details-summary">
            <span class="map-page__details-kicker">What you&rsquo;re seeing</span>
            <span class="map-page__details-title" id="map-about-title">An economic impact study, run live.</span>
            <span class="map-page__details-chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="map-page__about-grid">
            <div class="map-page__about-card">
              <h3 class="map-page__about-card-head">What it is</h3>
              <p class="map-page__about-card-body">An economic impact study estimates how a project, program, or investment ripples through a regional economy: direct spending, supplier purchases, the wages workers earn and then spend, and the jobs and tax revenue all of that supports.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="map-page__about-card">
              <h3 class="map-page__about-card-head">What you'll see on the map</h3>
              <p class="map-page__about-card-body">The source region lights up in gold to mark the direct effect, while teal flows trace the indirect and induced spillover into the neighbouring regions. Total impact, jobs, and labour income land in the row beneath the map, and clicking another region runs a fresh study that updates everything in seconds.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="map-page__about-card">
              <h3 class="map-page__about-card-head">How fast</h3>
              <p class="map-page__about-card-body">A standard study takes minutes instead of months. The legacy path runs a single consulting engagement per study and ships months later, while Lumecon runs the same mainstream economics under a workflow built for cloud infrastructure, modern data, and AI from day one.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- "Why it matters." Direct audience-facing framing — the
         language anyone presenting impact numbers to a council, a
         board, a foundation, or a federal office actually has to
         use. Collapsible because the visitor either needs this
         framing (and wants it expanded) or doesn't (and skips). -->
    <section class="map-page__why-matters" aria-labelledby="map-why-title">
      <div class="map-page__about-inner">
        <details class="map-page__details map-page__details--invert">
          <summary class="map-page__details-summary">
            <span class="map-page__details-kicker map-page__details-kicker--invert">Why it matters</span>
            <span class="map-page__details-title" id="map-why-title">When the room asks why they should care.</span>
            <span class="map-page__details-chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="map-page__why-body">
            <p class="map-page__why-lede">Council chambers, board rooms, foundation review panels, Congressional staffers&rsquo; offices, and tribal councils all ask the same question of any organization that walks in with an ask: prove it. Prove the jobs you support, the wages you generate, the businesses that exist because you do, and the tax base you sustain. Lumecon hands you the numbers each of those rooms respects, in the language each of those rooms speaks.</p>
            <ul class="map-page__why-rooms" aria-label="Audiences that recognize these numbers">
              <li class="map-page__why-room">
                <h3 class="map-page__why-room-head">Councils, boards, and legislators</h3>
                <p class="map-page__why-room-body">Lumecon ships the defensible figures councils, boards, legislators, and policymakers actually weigh: jobs supported, payroll generated, local supplier spend, and multi-year capital impact. The kind of numbers that move a vote, a budget line, or a bill instead of a memo back to staff.</p>
              </li>
              <li class="map-page__why-room">
                <h3 class="map-page__why-room-head">Funders, grantmakers, and donors</h3>
                <p class="map-page__why-room-body">Federal grant programs (EDA, HUD CDBG, DOT BUILD, USDA Rural Development, NTIA, EPA) and private foundations want the same thing: jobs, private investment, and regional benefit with a credible source behind the numbers. Lumecon produces those figures with the methodology attached, ready to drop into a grant narrative or an annual report, and measured the same way every year so results stay comparable across grantees and across time.</p>
              </li>
              <li class="map-page__why-room">
                <h3 class="map-page__why-room-head">Advocacy, marketing, and comms</h3>
                <p class="map-page__why-room-body">One defensible jobs-and-investment number runs through every government-affairs deck, op-ed, regulatory comment, and trade-association testimony, then reshapes into annual-report headlines, social cards, donor one-pagers, and recruiting collateral. The whole pipeline pulls from the same figures the board approved instead of a consultant rebuilding the math for each new pitch.</p>
              </li>
              <li class="map-page__why-room">
                <h3 class="map-page__why-room-head">Public and press</h3>
                <p class="map-page__why-room-body">Reporters and the public get the plain-language version of the same study: how much local spending stayed in the region, how many local workers were hired, and what the project bought that would not have been bought otherwise.</p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- "How the model learns." NetworkSection lives here, at the
         bottom of /map, NOT on the homepage. The reason it makes
         sense in this slot specifically: visitors who've just run
         a live study are the ones who care how the model behind
         the study stays accurate. -->
    <NetworkSection />

    <!-- CTA band below the map. Compact, single-row on desktop, so
         the visitor who just played with the demo gets a clear
         next step without scrolling past a wall of marketing. -->
    <section class="map-page__cta" aria-labelledby="map-cta-text">
      <div class="map-page__cta-inner">
        <p class="map-page__cta-text" id="map-cta-text">
          Like what you see? Sign up to run studies on your own data.
        </p>
        <div class="map-page__cta-buttons">
          <a href="/signup" class="btn">Sign up</a>
          <a href="/pricing" class="btn btn--ghost">See pricing</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
